Reasoning: This paper does not explicitly focus on computer science, but rather on the research performance of professors in the sciences. However, the paper does use quantitative methods to analyze data and track the performance of scientists over time, which suggests a potential fit with several arXiv CS sub-categories. Specifically, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CY (Computers and Society) may be relevant given the focus on analyzing patterns of behavior and performance among scientists. cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.DL (Digital Libraries) may also be relevant given the use of data analysis techniques to track research productivity. Finally, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) may be relevant given the potential complexity of analyzing and interpreting large datasets of research performance.
